@NODE "How To Use" "How To Use"
@TOC "MAIN"

                              @{U}HACK ATTACK III@{UU}


                                How To Use



Well, anyone who has ever used ZXAM POKE Guide will know how to use this
as there are one or two slight similarites (ahem!)...

Anyway, just load up the emulator and the game, but don't run it. Then
load up this cool file and just pick the game you want, and click on the
options you want installed.

Or, if you want to be a bit different, you can use a file manager (like
Disk Master or DOpus) and go into the game's POKE directly by just reading
the POKE itsef instead of the main program (like say you wanted to cheat
at "Hawk Storm", you could just go into the "H" sub-directory and double
click on "HAWK_STORM.GUIDE" and go from there). The only exception to this
method is a game like After The War, or Game Over where there are more
than one part. Here you would click on the POKE for the section of the
game you wanted (eg "AFTER_THE_WAR_1.GUIDE as opposed to the file
"AFTER_THE_WAR.GUIDE"). It probably sounds more complicated than it is.

Umm.. I can't really think of any other instructions you need to know.
Oh yes, you MUST have REXXMAST running BEFORE you load the emulator,
otherwise it won't work. This is nothing to do with my file, but rather
the emulator looks to see if Rexxmast is running when it runs, and if
not doesn't install the Arexx commands... Well, that's the way I see it
anyway. If it's wrong, then tough luck on me I guess....

And that's it. Once you've finished choosing the options you need, just
click on RUN on the emulator's GUI.

Oh wait a minute.. I nearly forgot.. Some of the POKEs are for a
specified amount of something (eg. x lives). These work a bit
differently.. If you click on the POKE's button, it will put the value
at the maximum possible value (usually 255). If you don't want that
many, you enter the POKE written on the screen into the POKE option
on the emulator GUI, and press the POKE button.

For example...


Ball Crazy has this POKE available...

Lives = x                28086,x (x= 1-255).

If you click the button, you will get 255 lives (the maximum amount).
However, if you only want 10 lives, you would go to the "POKE" option
on the emulator GUI panel, and put the 28086 in the left hand box
(that's the one before the comma), and the number of lives you want
(eg 10) in the right box (after the comma). Then press POKE..


Hope that's explained simply enough for everyone....


Rastan.
@endnode

@NODE "Updates" "Updates"
@TOC "MAIN"

                              @{U}HACK ATTACK III@{UU}

               UPDATES - How to make your own & getting more



Well, because this program is modular, making update POKEs is easy!

All you do is get the multiface POKE (Important <g>), make sure that
it works (Also important <g>), and get a text editor and load up an
existing POKE starting with the same letter as your new hack, and change
the appropriate details and save it off under a new name. You can then
change the menu for that letter and add the new game on.

I'm sorry if this explanation is a bit crap, but I've been working
on this thing for so long that it seems SO easy for me, that I may
skip a bit on the explanation....

You can then do what you like with your new POKE.. You can compile
a lot of them and then release them, and anyone who downloads them
can just change their menu themselves.

If you are releasing updates, PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE(!!) make sure that
they WORK, as there is nothing worse than getting a multiface POKE
you've been desperately looking for, installing it, then finding it
doesn't work at all... I should know, I went through EVERY one in
ZXAMPOKE, every issue of YS (except 2) and Crash (except 5), and a
load of Sinclair User mags testing every one of them where possible.

Oh, and if you could make sure that the POKEs are set out in a
half-decently organised manner, that'd be nice. Just use the ones 
I've done as a template and you should be OK...

Ermm... That's about it really.... Only, if you do release POKEs,
don't be lame and say you did them yourself if you just ripped them
out of a mag! That really sucks!

In case anyone clicked here thinking they were going to read about
updates from me, don't worry.. I will be releasing POKE lists every
once in a while for your enjoyment....

Rastan.

@endnode

@NODE "A Word From Me" "A Word From Me"
@TOC "MAIN"

                              @{U}HACK ATTACK III@{UU}


                           A QUICK NOTE FROM ME


Hello Speccy fans, and welcome to my contribution to the ever-growing Speccy emulation
sensation that's sweeping the nation (sorry about that, won't do it again!).

Almost every self-respecting Amiga owner and Speccy fan has the cool ZXAM emulator by
Antonio J. Pomar Rossello, and a great deal of those people will have ZXAMPoke by 
Richard Korber.

I personally thought ZXAMPoke was a damn fine effort at a difficult idea - to have a
large amount of Speccy POKEs compiled and organised in a easy-to-use fashion. However,
the more I used it, I found a few @{"flaws" link flaws} which I thought could be
improved upon.

Once I had ironed these out (I think?!), the result is here in front of you. I hope
you like it. I've worked hard on it, testing EVERY one of the POKEs I could using
Speccy Sensations 2. If I found a POKE which didn't work, I'd try and hack the
game myself.

Oh, if anyone is wondering how this program got its name, well number 1 was
published, 2 was meant for released but then YS was stopped on the issue it was
meant to be released on (DOH!!!), so this is the next one...


@{B}@{U}GREETS@{UU}@{UB}

First up I really MUST thank Antonio J. Pomar Rossello (author of the ZXAM
emulator) and Richard Korber (author of ZXAMPOKE), without whom this wouldn't
be possible.

Also, all the cool dudes who hacked the Speccy games, and the mags they were
published in, especially YS - THANK YOU!

Oh yeah, and hello to the guys who were in my group, but weren't really -
M, J and R (though R did write the two HAs). They never actually hacked a
single game. It was all done by me. Hopefully that should mean something
to someone?

I'd like to individually thank (as many as I can remember)

@{u}SPECCY@{uu}

Jon North - Cool dude! Did you ever get the recording contract?
Jon Pillar - Thanks for the chats (and the cash) - Going back a bit here!
Linda Barker - The best looking Tipshop writer (and Ed)..
Jonathan Davies - Not as good looking, but still cool.
Ray - Get your A1200 fixed, and your Speccy back. I have a project for you!
Matt - I'd ask you, but you sold your Speccy for a Sam.
Jamie - The only speccy hacker who only owned an Amstrad (and NEVER HACKED!)
@{"Richard Swann" LINK R_Swann}
The Speccy Sensations compilers - Cool, but still a lot of duplication!

@{u}THE REST@{UU}

Cobra - Still a cool dude, despite being a PC owner now (Spit!)
Renegade - Thanks for the help m8 (and the [nearly] job)... And CONGRATS!
All the cool Access dudes across the globe. Sorry I can't name you all
individually, but it would take too long.
All the dudes I know on D&C
The cool guy at Active Software... I never did catch your name :)
Digger - Are you EVER in? Either working or out on the pull...


That's it for the greets, but before I go.. As it's Christmas (look, it
is at the moment I'm typing this, so don't argue OK?!), I've included a
secret goodie with this file. @{"How do you find it?" LINK "Secret"}

Oh, before I go. If any Speccy & Klondike fans are reading, I have done
a few Klondike cardsets using both Speccy LOADing SCREEN$ (hehe), and
game inlay cards as well.. Keep your eyes peeled for them and all of my
other sets as well! (End of obscenely blatant plug!)

Rastan.
@endnode

